      Whole crop management
    </a>
    <div id="Whole" class="collapse">
      <img src="images/option_30.png">
      <img src="images/option_32.png">
      <p>Less intensive management (reduced inputs of pesticides and fertilisers)
        of crops on a field scale can also benefit arable flowers. This is
        particularly evident in areas where root crops such as fodder beet are
        grown for livestock feed over the winter, cereals are undersown with
        legumes for whole crop silage, or low input cereals are harvested for
        grain. Plants that grow in these cropped situations include more robust
        species like 
        <a href="#species/26">cornflower</a>,
        <a href="#species/61">corn marigold</a>,
        <a href="#species/83">weasel’s-snout</a> and <a href="#species/71"> venus’s-looking-glass</a>.
        Below is a summary of some of the
        options under agri-environment schemes to provide this habitat:
